%[text] # R02: PK/PD Simulation — 1-Compartment PK/PD Model
%[text] EasyMolKit Research -- Layer 4
%[text] ## Story
%[text] Suppose a hospital formulary committee is recommending standard dosing intervals for four common over-the-counter drugs (Aspirin, Ibuprofen, Acetaminophen, Caffeine).
%[text] The clinical question here is, "All four molecules satisfy Lipinski's Rule of Five (Ro5), but how do their 24-hour blood concentration-time profiles differ?"
%[text] Lipinski Ro5 indicates "Can the body absorb it?" Pharmacokinetics (PK) considers the question "How much and for how long does it stay in the body?"
%[text] Even for two molecules that both satisfy Ro5, $C(max)$, $T(max)$, and $t(1/2)$ can vary significantly. Notice that these values depend on metabolism and tissue distribution, not directly on molecular weight, LogP, HBD, or HBA.
%[text] ## Learning Objectives
%[text] In this exercise, you will:
%[text] 1. Apply Lipinski Ro5 to confirm that the four drugs are structurally suitable for oral absorption.
%[text] 2. Understand the mathematical structure of a 1-compartment oral PK model (two first-order ODEs).
%[text] 3. Programmatically build a SimBiology model and simulate 24-hour plasma concentration profiles.
%[text] 4. Calculate and compare $C(max)$, $T(max)$, AUC, and $t(1/2)$.
%[text] 5. Apply the Emax Pharmacodynamics (PD) model to estimate the time each drug exceeds EC50 (50% maximum effect threshold).
%[text] 6. Investigate the correlation between Lipinski descriptors and key PK metrics, and understand why they do not correlate.
%[text] 7. Understand why $CL$ and $Vd$ (not MW or LogP) determine $t(1/2)$. \
%[text] ## Prerequisites
%[text] - Completion of F02 (Physicochemical Calculations) and S02 (Drug Filters) is required.
%[text] - Completion of A10 (Lead Optimization) is recommended.
%[text] - SimBiology Toolbox is recommended, but if not installed, Sections 4–5 will fall back to ode45. \
%[text] ## Environment
%[text] SimBiology Toolbox is required for the main simulation path. The ode45 fallback produces numerically equivalent results to the SimBiology path.
%[text] ## Data
%[text] - data/list/fda\_drugs.csv — 200 FDA-approved drugs (ChEMBL, CC-BY-SA 3.0) \
%[text] ## References
%[text] - Rowland M & Tozer TN (2011) Clinical Pharmacokinetics and Pharmacodynamics (4th ed). Lippincott Williams & Wilkins. ISBN 978-0781750097. \[Aspirin PK; General 1-Compartment Theory\]
%[text] - Rainsford KD (2009) Ibuprofen: pharmacology, efficacy and safety. Inflammopharmacology 17:275-342. doi:10.1007/s10787-009-0016-x \[Ibuprofen PK Parameters\]
%[text] - Forrest JAH et al. (1982) Paracetamol metabolism in chronic liver disease. Eur J Clin Pharmacol 22:69-73. doi:10.1007/BF00544584 \[Acetaminophen PK Parameters\]
%[text] - Kalow W & Tang BK (1991) Caffeine as a metabolic probe. Clin Pharmacol Ther 49:44-48. doi:10.1038/clpt.1991.6 \[Caffeine PK Parameters\]
%[text] - Lipinski CA et al. (2001) Experimental and computational approaches to estimate solubility and permeability in drug discovery. Adv Drug Deliv Rev 46:3-26. doi:10.1016/S0169-409X(00)00129-0 \[Ro5 and Oral Absorption Prediction\]
%[text] - Hill AV (1910) The possible effects of the aggregation of the molecules of haemoglobin on its dissociation curves. J Physiol 40:iv-vii. \[Origin of Emax / Hill Equation\] \
%[text] Duration: 45–90 minutes | Execution: Run each section with Ctrl+Enter.
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:88af741f]
%[text] Warm up the Python/RDKit process.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");   % Methane -- lightweight molecule
clear mol_warmup;
%[text] Check for the presence of SimBiology Toolbox.
hasSimbio = license("test", "simbiology");
if hasSimbio %[output:group:88e12648]
    logInfo("R02: SimBiology Toolbox detected. Using main PK solver."); %[output:6f47cbc5]
else
    logWarn("R02: SimBiology Toolbox not found. Using ode45 fallback.");
    logWarn("     Results are numerically identical to SimBiology path.");
    logWarn("     Install campus license to use SimBiology.");
end %[output:group:88e12648]
logInfo("R02: Setup complete."); %[output:05197c1d]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Story — From Lipinski to Blood Concentration
%[text] ### Stage 1 — Structural Filter (Lipinski Ro5)
%[text] Lipinski Ro5 is a rule to predict whether the physicochemical properties of a molecule are suitable for passive permeability in the intestines.
%[text] Molecules that pass Ro5 are structurally suitable for oral administration, but solubility, efflux transporters, and first-pass metabolism also affect absorption, so passing Ro5 does not guarantee absorption.
%[text] Ro5 thresholds are shown below; borderline cases allow up to 1 violation.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Descriptor | Threshold | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | MW | $\\leq$ 500 g/mol | Upper limit for intestinal permeability |
%[text] | LogP | $\\leq$ 5 | Lipophilicity — too high reduces water solubility |
%[text] | HBD | $\\leq$ 5 | Number of hydrogen bond donors — too many worsen membrane permeability |
%[text] | HBA | $\\leq$ 10 | Number of hydrogen bond acceptors |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] ### Stage 2 — Pharmacokinetic Simulation (1-Compartment Model)
%[text] Assuming oral absorption is possible, the time course of drug concentration in plasma can be described by a 1-compartment model.
%[text] Two state variables describe the system: the gut compartment (drug awaiting absorption, $A(gut)$ \[mg\]) and the central compartment (drug in systemic plasma, $A(c)$ \[mg\]).
%[text] 
%[text] Initial conditions reflect the physical situation of oral administration.
%[text] $A(gut)(0) = F \\cdot Dose$ — The amount multiplied by bioavailability $F$ initially enters the gut.
%[text] $A(c)(0) = 0$ — Immediately after administration, there is no drug in the plasma.
%[text] 
%[text] The governing ODEs are:
%[text] $\\frac{dA(gut)}{dt} = -k(a) \\cdot A(gut)$ — Drug in the gut is absorbed into plasma at a first-order rate constant $k(a)$ \[$\\text{h}^{-1}$\].
%[text] $\\frac{dA(c)}{dt} = k(a) \\cdot A(gut) - k(e) \\cdot A(c)$ — The difference between inflow by absorption and outflow by elimination determines the amount of drug in plasma.
%[text] Plasma concentration $C(plasma)$ \[mg/L\] is $C(plasma) = A(c) / Vd$ ($Vd$: volume of distribution \[L\]).
%[text] 
%[text] The elimination rate constant is $k(e) = CL / Vd$ ($CL$: total clearance \[L/h\]).
%[text] The half-life is derived from this relationship as $t(1/2) = Vd \\cdot \\ln 2 / CL$.
%[text] As this equation shows, $t(1/2)$ is determined by $CL$ and $Vd$, not by molecular weight or LogP.
%[text] 
%[text] Parameter definitions (literature values for a 70 kg adult):
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Symbol | Unit | Meaning |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | $Dose$ | mg | Single oral dose |
%[text] | $F$ | — | Oral bioavailability (0–1) |
%[text] | $k(a)$ | $\\text{h}^{-1}$ | First-order absorption rate constant |
%[text] | $Vd$ | L | Apparent volume of distribution |
%[text] | $CL$ | L/h | Total clearance (metabolism + renal) |
%[text] | $k(e)$ | $\\text{h}^{-1}$ | Elimination rate constant $= CL / Vd$ |
%[text] | $t(1/2)$ | h | Elimination half-life $= Vd \\cdot \\ln 2 / CL$ |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] Key PK indices derived from the simulation:
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Index | Unit | Definition |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | $C(max)$ | mg/L | Maximum plasma concentration during simulation |
%[text] | $T(max)$ | h | Time to reach $C(max)$ |
%[text] | AUC | mg·h/L | Area under the concentration-time curve (analytical solution: $F \\cdot Dose / CL$) |
%[text] | $t(1/2)$ | h | Elimination half-life $= Vd \\cdot \\ln 2 / CL$ |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] ### Emax Pharmacodynamic Model
%[text] The Emax (Hill) equation relates plasma concentration $C$ to pharmacological effect $E$.
%[text] The general form is $E(C) = \\frac{E(max) \\cdot C^n}{EC50^n + C^n}$ ($n$: Hill coefficient, EC50: concentration for 50% maximum effect).
%[text] For many small molecule drugs without cooperative binding, $n = 1$, simplifying to $E(C) = \\frac{E(max) \\cdot C}{EC50 + C}$.
%[text] Notice that: $E(0) = 0$ (no drug, no effect), $E(EC50) = E(max) / 2$ (this defines EC50), and $C \\to \\infty$ gives $E \\to E(max)$ (saturating bounded response).
%[text] The time above EC50, $T(eff)$, is the period where $E \\geq 50\\%\\,E(max)$ and guides dosing interval selection.
logInfo("1-Compartment Oral PK Model:"); %[output:183811b6]
logInfo("  A(gut)(0) = F * Dose,  A(c)(0) = 0"); %[output:371ab0e5]
logInfo("  dA(gut)/dt = -k(a) * A(gut)"); %[output:4f7cc30c]
logInfo("  dA(c)/dt   =  k(a) * A(gut) - k(e) * A(c),  k(e) = CL/Vd"); %[output:61f49283]
logInfo("  C(plasma)  =  A(c) / Vd  [mg/L]"); %[output:62f5e5af]
logInfo("  Emax PD:    E = Emax * C / (EC50 + C)"); %[output:2a8d863e]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: Loading Drug Library and Lipinski Screening
%[text] ### Using Lipinski Ro5 as a Preliminary Filter
%[text] In actual drug discovery pipelines, thousands of virtual compounds are filtered by Ro5 before costly ADMET experiments. Even if Ro5 fails, they may be effective as injectables or topical drugs, but their priority decreases for oral development.
%[text] FDA-approved oral drugs already reach patients, becoming "gold standard" data, and almost all should pass Ro5.
%[text] Macrolides and natural product-derived drugs utilizing active transporters, which exist as exceptions, serve as educational case studies demonstrating the limitations of Ro5.
DATA_FILE     = "data/list/fda_drugs.csv";
rawTbl        = readtable(DATA_FILE, TextType="string");
LIPINSKI_DESC = ["MolWt", "LogP", "NumHDonors", "NumHAcceptors"];
logInfo("Loaded %d entries from %s", height(rawTbl), DATA_FILE); %[output:8f062c70]
%[text] Parsing molecules.
nLib  = height(rawTbl);
mols  = cell(1, nLib);
names = strings(1, nLib);
valid = false(1, nLib);
for k = 1:nLib
    try
        mols{k}  = emk.mol.fromSmiles(rawTbl.SMILES(k));
        names(k) = rawTbl.Name(k);
        valid(k) = true;
    catch
        % Ignore unparsable entries
    end
end
validIdx = find(valid);
mols     = mols(validIdx);
names    = names(validIdx);
nValid   = numel(mols);
logInfo("Parsed %d / %d molecules.", nValid, nLib); %[output:2c7feb1b]
%[text] Batch calculation of Lipinski descriptors.
descTbl = emk.descriptor.batchCalculate(mols, LIPINSKI_DESC);
%[text] Combine with name column and exclude NaN rows.
nameTbl = table(names(:), VariableNames=["Name"]);
fullTbl = [nameTbl, descTbl];
fullTbl = rmmissing(fullTbl);
%[text] Apply Lipinski Ro5 (MaxViolations=1 is standard practice).
ro5Tbl  = emk.filter.lipinski(fullTbl, MaxViolations=1); %[output:4c83b673]
passIdx = ro5Tbl.Pass_Ro5;
nPass   = sum(passIdx);
nFail   = sum(~passIdx);
logInfo("Lipinski Ro5 (MaxViolations=1):  %d PASS  /  %d FAIL  /  %d total", ... %[output:group:7745695d] %[output:248d86c1]
    nPass, nFail, height(ro5Tbl)); %[output:group:7745695d] %[output:248d86c1]
for v = 0:4 %[output:group:6face3e1]
    n_v = sum(ro5Tbl.Violations_Ro5 == v);
    if n_v > 0
        logInfo("  %d violations: %d molecules", v, n_v); %[output:07d6867c]
    end
end %[output:group:6face3e1]
%[text] Display up to 5 examples of failures (educational cases like macrolides).
if nFail > 0 %[output:group:84246c5d]
    failNames = ro5Tbl.Name(~passIdx);
    failViols = ro5Tbl.Violations_Ro5(~passIdx);
    logInfo("Ro5 Failures (many are macrolides or natural product-derived drugs):"); %[output:1be84097]
    for k = 1:min(5, nFail)
        logInfo("  %s  [%d violations]", failNames(k), failViols(k)); %[output:6b4fdb2d]
    end
end %[output:group:84246c5d]
%[text] Visualize the distribution of violations with a bar graph.
figure("Name", "R02 Sec2: Lipinski Violation Distribution"); %[output:34fed3fc]
vc = arrayfun(@(v) sum(ro5Tbl.Violations_Ro5 == v), 0:4);
bar(0:4, vc, FaceColor="#4C72B0", EdgeColor="white"); %[output:34fed3fc]
xlabel("Number of Ro5 Violations"); %[output:34fed3fc]
ylabel("Number of Molecules"); %[output:34fed3fc]
title("Lipinski Violation Distribution — FDA Drug Library"); %[output:34fed3fc]
xticklabels({"0 (Pass)", "1 (Pass*)", "2 (Fail)", "3 (Fail)", "4 (Fail)"}); %[output:34fed3fc]
grid on; %[output:34fed3fc]
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Literature PK Parameter Database
%[text] ### Measured PK Parameters vs Predicted PK Parameters
%[text] Computational ADMET tools (pkCSM, SwissADME, etc.) estimate PK parameters from 2D structures, but the uncertainty in $Vd$ and $CL$ is typically around ±50%.
%[text] We use gold-standard measured values for a 70 kg adult to eliminate prediction noise and study PK model dynamics.
%[text] 
%[text] Each parameter is measured as follows.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Parameter | Measurement Method |
%[text] | --- | --- |
%[text] | $F$ | AUC ratio of IV and oral administration: $F = AUC(oral) / AUC(iv)$ |
%[text] | $Vd$ | From IV dose and extrapolated $C(0)$: $Vd = Dose\_{IV} / C(0)$ |
%[text] | $CL$ | From AUC and dose: $CL = F \\cdot Dose / AUC(inf)$ |
%[text] | $k(a)$ | Fitting the rising phase of the oral C–t curve |
%[text:table]
%[text] All parameters below are population averages; individual values vary with age, weight, renal/hepatic function, and CYP450 genotype.
pkDB = struct();
%[text] Aspirin (Acetylsalicylic Acid): Rapidly hydrolyzed to salicylate in the body (parent drug $t(1/2) \\approx$ 20 min). Source: Rowland & Tozer (2011), Chapter 13.
pkDB(1).Name   = "Aspirin";
pkDB(1).SMILES = "CC(=O)Oc1ccccc1C(=O)O";
pkDB(1).Dose   = 500;    % mg  (standard analgesic dose)
pkDB(1).F      = 0.68;   % Bioavailability
pkDB(1).ka     = 1.40;   % h^-1 (absorption rate constant)
pkDB(1).Vd     = 11.0;   % L
pkDB(1).CL     = 23.0;   % L/h  (very fast; due to hydrolysis)
pkDB(1).EC50   = 3.0;    % mg/L  (analgesic; approximate)
pkDB(1).Color  = "#E24A33";
%[text] Ibuprofen: Anti-inflammatory drug via COX (cyclooxygenase) inhibition. Source: Rainsford (2009).
pkDB(2).Name   = "Ibuprofen";
pkDB(2).SMILES = "CC(C)Cc1ccc(cc1)C(C)C(=O)O";
pkDB(2).Dose   = 400;    % mg
pkDB(2).F      = 0.87;
pkDB(2).ka     = 3.00;   % h^-1
pkDB(2).Vd     = 9.0;    % L
pkDB(2).CL     = 3.6;    % L/h
pkDB(2).EC50   = 5.0;    % mg/L  (COX inhibition; approximate)
pkDB(2).Color  = "#348ABD";
%[text] Acetaminophen (Paracetamol): Antipyretic analgesic, primarily metabolized in the liver. Source: Forrest et al. (1982).
pkDB(3).Name   = "Acetaminophen";
pkDB(3).SMILES = "CC(=O)Nc1ccc(O)cc1";
pkDB(3).Dose   = 500;    % mg
pkDB(3).F      = 0.88;
pkDB(3).ka     = 2.00;   % h^-1
pkDB(3).Vd     = 50.0;   % L  (moderate tissue distribution)
pkDB(3).CL     = 18.0;   % L/h
pkDB(3).EC50   =  5.0;   % mg/L  (analgesic; approximate)
pkDB(3).Color  = "#988ED5";
%[text] Caffeine: CNS stimulant antagonizing adenosine receptors, with nearly 100% oral bioavailability. Source: Kalow & Tang (1991).
pkDB(4).Name   = "Caffeine";
pkDB(4).SMILES = "Cn1cnc2c1c(=O)n(C)c(=O)n2C";
pkDB(4).Dose   = 200;    % mg  (common coffee/energy drink dose)
pkDB(4).F      = 1.00;   % Nearly complete oral bioavailability
pkDB(4).ka     = 1.80;   % h^-1
pkDB(4).Vd     = 37.0;   % L
pkDB(4).CL     = 2.5;    % L/h
pkDB(4).EC50   = 1.0;    % mg/L  (adenosine antagonism; approximate)
pkDB(4).Color  = "#777777";
nDrugs = numel(pkDB);
%[text] Display the list of literature PK parameters ($t(1/2) = Vd \\cdot \\ln 2 / CL$ derived).
logInfo("Literature PK Parameters (70 kg adult):"); %[output:4c01029d]
logInfo("  %-16s %6s %5s %6s %6s %6s %6s %6s", ... %[output:group:1db8736f] %[output:50a2ea39]
    "Drug", "Dose", "F", "ka", "Vd", "CL", "t1/2", "EC50"); %[output:group:1db8736f] %[output:50a2ea39]
logInfo("  %-16s %6s %5s %6s %6s %6s %6s %6s", ... %[output:group:4960941e] %[output:32f92169]
    "", "mg", "--", "h^-1", "L", "L/h", "h", "mg/L"); %[output:group:4960941e] %[output:32f92169]
logInfo("  %s", repmat("-", 1, 70)); %[output:3f8c7ac1]
for k = 1:nDrugs %[output:group:790bef43]
    pk     = pkDB(k);
    t_half = pk.Vd * log(2) / pk.CL;
    logInfo("  %-16s %6.0f %5.2f %6.2f %6.1f %6.1f %6.2f %6.1f", ... %[output:4f4135db]
        pk.Name, pk.Dose, pk.F, pk.ka, pk.Vd, pk.CL, t_half, pk.EC50); %[output:4f4135db]
end %[output:group:790bef43]
%[text] Check Lipinski Ro5 compliance for each of the 4 drugs.
logInfo("Checking Lipinski Ro5 for PK database drugs:"); %[output:021a35ce]
for k = 1:nDrugs %[output:group:2ce23bb6]
    mol_k = emk.mol.fromSmiles(pkDB(k).SMILES);
    d_k   = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol_k, LIPINSKI_DESC);
    row_k = struct2table(d_k);
    row_k = emk.filter.lipinski(row_k, MaxViolations=1); %[output:0f7e7cac] %[output:4a99dd49] %[output:3900f8c8] %[output:2ac55ca6]
    if row_k.Pass_Ro5
        status = "PASS";
    else
        status = "FAIL";
    end
    logInfo("  %-16s MW=%5.1f  LogP=%+5.2f  HBD=%d  HBA=%d  -->  %s", ... %[output:8c08abe6] %[output:5860f19c] %[output:663a9183] %[output:31f19db8]
        pkDB(k).Name, d_k.MolWt, d_k.LogP, ... %[output:8c08abe6] %[output:5860f19c] %[output:663a9183] %[output:31f19db8]
        d_k.NumHDonors, d_k.NumHAcceptors, status); %[output:8c08abe6] %[output:5860f19c] %[output:663a9183] %[output:31f19db8]
end %[output:group:2ce23bb6]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Simulation of 1-Compartment PK Profile
%[text] ### SimBiology vs ode45
%[text] SimBiology lets you build models from compartments, species, and reactions, mirroring the structure of pharmacological literature.
%[text] Advantages include readable model graphs (explicit species/compartments/reactions), built-in dosing and unit support, and scalability to 2-compartment or population PK via sbiofit.
%[text] Here, we use a compartment with a volume of 1 L, so the amount is equal to the concentration.
%[text] Set the initial amount of species Drug\_gut to $F \\cdot Dose$ \[mg\] and Drug\_c to 0.
%[text] The rate of reaction 1 (Drug\_gut → Drug\_c) is $k(a) \\cdot Drug\_{gut}$ \[mg/h\], and the rate of reaction 2 (Drug\_c → null) is $k(e) \\cdot Drug\_{c}$ \[mg/h\].
%[text] Dividing the output Drug\_c \[mg\] by $Vd$ gives the plasma concentration $C(plasma)$ \[mg/L\].
%[text] If SimBiology is not available, integrate the same ODE system with ode45 to obtain numerically equivalent results.
T_SIM = 24;    % h -- simulation duration
N_PTS = 1000;  % number of uniform output time points
tspan = linspace(0, T_SIM, N_PTS);
pkSim = struct();
for k = 1:nDrugs %[output:group:8113d850]
    pk         = pkDB(k);
    ke         = pk.CL / pk.Vd;        % elimination rate constant (h^-1)
    y0         = [pk.F * pk.Dose; 0];  % [A_gut; A_c] at t=0 (mg)
    simSuccess = false;
    if hasSimbio
        try
            % --- Main SimBiology Path ---
            m = sbiomodel(sprintf("PK_%s", pk.Name));
            % 2 compartments (volume=1 => treat amount as concentration)
            gut_cmp = addcompartment(m, "gut",     1);
            cen_cmp = addcompartment(m, "central", 1);
            % Species: initial amount (mg)
            addspecies(gut_cmp, "Drug_gut", pk.F * pk.Dose);
            addspecies(cen_cmp, "Drug_c",   0);
            % Parameters
            addparameter(m, "ka", pk.ka);
            addparameter(m, "ke", ke);
            % Reactions (amount-based; volume=1 => rate unit [mg/h])
            r_abs            = addreaction(m, "gut.Drug_gut -> central.Drug_c");
            r_abs.ReactionRate = "ka * Drug_gut";
            r_elim             = addreaction(m, "central.Drug_c -> null");
            r_elim.ReactionRate = "ke * Drug_c";
            % Solver settings
            cs            = getconfigset(m);
            cs.StopTime   = T_SIM;
            cs.SolverType = "ode45";
            cs.SolverOptions.OutputTimes         = tspan(:);  % uniform output points
            cs.SolverOptions.AbsoluteTolerance   = 1e-9;      % tight AbsTol -- suppress dense-output noise at near-zero conc.
            % Run simulation and extract Drug_c (pass cs to enable OutputTimes)
            [t_raw, x_raw, simNames] = sbiosimulate(m, cs);
            idxC    = contains(simNames, "Drug_c");   % corresponds to "central.Drug_c" format
            A_c_raw = x_raw(:, idxC);
            % OutputTimes = tspan so no interpolation needed: directly amount/Vd -> concentration
            C_sim      = max(0, A_c_raw / pk.Vd);   % mg/L, non-negative
            t_sim      = t_raw(:);
            simSuccess = true;
            logInfo("  [SimBiology] Simulation completed for %s.", pk.Name); %[output:67872dcb] %[output:1a197881] %[output:3954d693] %[output:24c9315d]
        catch ME
            logWarn("SimBiology simulation failed for %s: %s", pk.Name, ME.message);
            logWarn("Falling back to ode45 for %s.", pk.Name);
        end
    end
    if ~simSuccess
        % --- ode45 Fallback Path ---
        odeFunc        = @(t, y) [-pk.ka * y(1); ...
                                   pk.ka * y(1) - ke * y(2)];
        [t_raw, y_raw] = ode45(odeFunc, tspan, y0);
        C_sim          = max(0, y_raw(:, 2) / pk.Vd);   % mg/L
        t_sim          = t_raw(:);
        logInfo("  [ode45 fallback] Simulation completed for %s.", pk.Name);
    end
    % Derived PK metrics
    [Cmax_k, imax] = max(C_sim);
    Tmax_k   = t_sim(imax);
    t_half_k = pk.Vd * log(2) / pk.CL;
    AUC_num  = trapz(t_sim, C_sim);           % numerical (24 h window)
    AUC_ana  = pk.F * pk.Dose / pk.CL;       % analytical AUC_inf
    pkSim(k).Name   = pk.Name;
    pkSim(k).t      = t_sim;
    pkSim(k).C      = C_sim;
    pkSim(k).Cmax   = Cmax_k;
    pkSim(k).Tmax   = Tmax_k;
    pkSim(k).t_half = t_half_k;
    pkSim(k).AUC    = AUC_num;
    pkSim(k).AUCana = AUC_ana;
    logInfo("  %s: Cmax=%.2f mg/L, Tmax=%.2f h, t1/2=%.2f h, AUC(24h)=%.1f (inf=%.1f) mg*h/L", ... %[output:4656c4ce] %[output:9a95f5e9] %[output:62f3bed7] %[output:7fa604c8]
        pk.Name, Cmax_k, Tmax_k, t_half_k, AUC_num, AUC_ana); %[output:4656c4ce] %[output:9a95f5e9] %[output:62f3bed7] %[output:7fa604c8]
end %[output:group:8113d850]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Visualization of Plasma Concentration Profiles
%[text] ### Understanding Concentration–Time Curves
%[text] A typical oral administration C–t curve has three phases. First is the absorption phase (ascending limb), governed by $k(a)$ and $F$. Next is the peak at $T(max)$ ($C(max)$), where absorption and elimination rates are equal. Finally, the elimination phase (descending limb) is logarithmic-linear with a slope of $-k(e) = -CL/Vd$.
%[text] 
%[text] On a logarithmic scale y-axis, the terminal elimination slope becomes linear, following $\\ln C = \\ln A - k(e) \\cdot t$ (slope $= -k(e) = -CL/Vd$). This linearity allows estimation of $k(e)$ from sparse clinical samples, forming the basis of therapeutic drug monitoring (TDM).
%[text] \--- Figure 1: Individual Profiles (2×2 Grid) ---
figure("Name", "R02 Sec5: Individual Plasma Concentration Profiles"); %[output:6ab8217c]
tiledlayout(2, 2, TileSpacing="compact", Padding="compact"); %[output:6ab8217c]
for k = 1:nDrugs
    nexttile; %[output:6ab8217c]
    plot(pkSim(k).t, pkSim(k).C, "Color", pkDB(k).Color, LineWidth=2);
    hold on;
    % EC50 threshold
    yline(pkDB(k).EC50, "--", sprintf("EC50=%.1f", pkDB(k).EC50), ...
        Color=pkDB(k).Color, LabelHorizontalAlignment="left", FontSize=8);
    % Cmax / Tmax annotation
    scatter(pkSim(k).Tmax, pkSim(k).Cmax, 80, "k", "filled", "^");
    text(pkSim(k).Tmax + 0.4, pkSim(k).Cmax, ...
        sprintf("C_{max}=%.1f", pkSim(k).Cmax), FontSize=8);
    xlabel("Time (h)");
    ylabel("Plasma Concentration C (mg/L)");
    title(sprintf("%s  (t_{1/2}=%.2f h)", pkDB(k).Name, pkSim(k).t_half));
    xlim([0, T_SIM]);
    ylim([0, pkSim(k).Cmax * 1.3]);
    grid on;  box on;
end
sgtitle("1-Compartment Oral PK — 24-Hour Plasma Profiles"); %[output:6ab8217c]
%[text] \--- Figure 2: All Drugs Overlaid ---
figure("Name", "R02 Sec5: All Drugs Overlaid"); %[output:4edd1286]
hold on; %[output:4edd1286]
for k = 1:nDrugs
    plot(pkSim(k).t, pkSim(k).C, "Color", pkDB(k).Color, ... %[output:4edd1286]
        LineWidth=2, DisplayName=pkSim(k).Name); %[output:4edd1286]
end
xlabel("Time (h)"); %[output:4edd1286]
ylabel("Plasma Concentration C (mg/L)"); %[output:4edd1286]
title("Plasma Concentration Comparison — All Drugs"); %[output:4edd1286]
legend(Location="northeast"); %[output:4edd1286]
xlim([0, T_SIM]); %[output:4edd1286]
grid on; %[output:4edd1286]
%[text] \--- Figure 3: PK Summary Bar Graph ---
figure("Name", "R02 Sec5: PK Summary Metrics"); %[output:75c573fc]
tiledlayout(1, 3, TileSpacing="compact"); %[output:75c573fc]
drug_labels = {pkDB.Name};
nexttile; %[output:75c573fc]
bar([pkSim.Cmax], FaceColor="#4C72B0"); %[output:75c573fc]
set(gca, "XTickLabel", drug_labels, "XTickLabelRotation", 30); %[output:75c573fc]
ylabel("C_{max} (mg/L)"); %[output:75c573fc]
title("Peak Concentration"); %[output:75c573fc]
grid on; %[output:75c573fc]
nexttile; %[output:75c573fc]
bar([pkSim.Tmax], FaceColor="#DD8452"); %[output:75c573fc]
set(gca, "XTickLabel", drug_labels, "XTickLabelRotation", 30); %[output:75c573fc]
ylabel("T_{max} (h)"); %[output:75c573fc]
title("Time to Peak"); %[output:75c573fc]
