%[text] ## Section 7: Lipinski Descriptors and PK Metrics Correlation
%[text] ### What Ro5 Predicts and What It Does Not
%[text] A common misconception is that "Lipinski-compliant molecules have good PK." Ro5 is designed to predict absorption (bioavailability $F$) and does not predict distribution ($Vd$) or elimination rates ($CL$, $t(1/2)$).
%[text] 
%[text] For this small dataset (n=4), LogP may show a weak correlation with $Vd$: lipophilic drugs tend to distribute into tissues, raising $Vd$, though exceptions are common.
%[text] MW does not correlate with $t(1/2)$. Clearance is governed by CYP450 enzyme activity and renal filtration, independent of molecular weight. All four drugs pass Ro5, yet $t(1/2)$ varies dramatically from 0.33 h (Aspirin) to 10.3 h (Caffeine).
%[text] Note that n=4 is too small for statistical conclusions. This section is a conceptual demonstration.
logInfo("Calculating RDKit descriptors for Lipinski correlation in pkDB drugs ..."); %[output:176503e4]
pkMW   = zeros(1, nDrugs);
pkLogP = zeros(1, nDrugs);
pkVd   = zeros(1, nDrugs);
pkHalf = zeros(1, nDrugs);
for k = 1:nDrugs
    mol_k    = emk.mol.fromSmiles(pkDB(k).SMILES);
    d_k      = emk.descriptor.calculate(mol_k, ["MolWt", "LogP"]);
    pkMW(k)  = d_k.MolWt;
    pkLogP(k)= d_k.LogP;
    pkVd(k)  = pkDB(k).Vd;
    pkHalf(k)= pkSim(k).t_half;
end
r_logp_vd  = corr(pkLogP(:), pkVd(:));
r_mw_thalf = corr(pkMW(:), pkHalf(:));
logInfo("Correlation (n=%d — conceptual demonstration only):", nDrugs); %[output:30e1c7b7]
logInfo("  LogP vs Vd   : Pearson r = %+.3f", r_logp_vd); %[output:76249084]
logInfo("  MW   vs t1/2 : Pearson r = %+.3f", r_mw_thalf); %[output:7ae233e1]
logInfo("  Note: n=4 is too small for statistical conclusions."); %[output:02ccf2d0]
figure("Name", "R02 Sec7: Lipinski Descriptors vs PK Metrics"); %[output:492be5a5]
tiledlayout(1, 2, TileSpacing="compact"); %[output:492be5a5]
nexttile; %[output:492be5a5]
hold on; %[output:492be5a5]
for k = 1:nDrugs
    scatter(pkLogP(k), pkVd(k), 100, "filled", ... %[output:492be5a5]
        MarkerFaceColor=pkDB(k).Color, MarkerEdgeColor="none"); %[output:492be5a5]
    text(pkLogP(k) + 0.05, pkVd(k) + 0.8, pkDB(k).Name, FontSize=9);
end
xlabel("LogP (Wildman-Crippen)"); %[output:492be5a5]
ylabel("Volume of Distribution V_d (L)"); %[output:492be5a5]
title(sprintf("LogP vs V_d  (r = %+.2f,  n=%d)", r_logp_vd, nDrugs)); %[output:492be5a5]
grid on;  box on; %[output:492be5a5]
nexttile; %[output:492be5a5]
hold on; %[output:492be5a5]
for k = 1:nDrugs
    scatter(pkMW(k), pkHalf(k), 100, "filled", ... %[output:492be5a5]
        MarkerFaceColor=pkDB(k).Color, MarkerEdgeColor="none"); %[output:492be5a5]
    text(pkMW(k) + 0.5, pkHalf(k) + 0.15, pkDB(k).Name, FontSize=9);
end
xlabel("Molecular Weight (g/mol)"); %[output:492be5a5]
ylabel("Elimination Half-life t_{1/2} (h)"); %[output:492be5a5]
title(sprintf("MW vs t_{1/2}  (r = %+.2f,  n=%d)", r_mw_thalf, nDrugs)); %[output:492be5a5]
grid on;  box on; %[output:492be5a5]
sgtitle("Lipinski Descriptors vs PK Metrics  (n=4, Conceptual Demonstration)"); %[output:492be5a5]
%%
%[text] ## Section 8: Summary
%[text] This exercise examined the relationship between Lipinski's Rule of 5 screening and 1-compartment pharmacokinetic simulation.
%[text] - **Role of Ro5 and PK**: Lipinski's Rule of 5 predicts oral bioavailability $F$, but does not predict distribution ($Vd$) or clearance ($CL$).
%[text] - **1-Compartment Model**: With the 4 parameters $k(a)$, $F$, $Vd$, and $CL$, the two ODEs $\\frac{dA(gut)}{dt} = -k(a) \\cdot A(gut)$ and $\\frac{dA(c)}{dt} = k(a) \\cdot A(gut) - k(e) \\cdot A(c)$ describe the plasma concentration profile.
%[text] - **Derived PK Metrics**: $C(max)$, $T(max)$, $t(1/2)$, and AUC can all be derived from $k(a)$, $F$, $Vd$, $CL$, and Dose.
%[text] - **Emax PD Model**: $E(C) = E(max) \\cdot C / (EC50 + C)$ links plasma concentration to pharmacological effect through EC50 (50% maximum effect threshold).
%[text] - **Efficacy Window**: The time $T(eff)$ above EC50 guides the selection of dosing intervals.
%[text] - **No Correlation between Ro5 and PK**: MW and LogP do not predict $t(1/2)$. $t(1/2) = Vd \\cdot \\ln 2 / CL$, where CYP450 metabolism governs $CL$, and tissue distribution governs $Vd$.
%[text] -  \

